title: Mathematics attainments for children ages 7 to 11 (key stage 2)
measure_summary:
This data measures the maths attainment of children in key stage 2 (years 3 to 6, when pupils are aged between 7 and 11).

The data covers the academic year 2015/16 (September 2015 to July 2016).
 
Key stage 2 test results range from 80 to 120 on a ‘scaled score’. (A ‘scaled score’ allows for variations in test difficulty year on year by standardising each pupil’s test results. This allows a clearer comparison between years.) 
 
Standards in maths are divided into 2 categories:
 
* expected standard

* higher standard
 
To reach the expected standard, pupils must have achieved a scaled score of 100 or more in their key stage 2 maths tests.
 
To reach the higher standard, pupils must have achieved a score of 110 or more in their key stage 2 maths tests.
 
The measure also looks at: 
 
* average scaled score 

* progress score
 
The average scaled score measures the average attainment of pupils in key stage 2 maths tests. This data compares the average scaled score for all children in England with the score for particular ethnic groups.  
 
The progress score measures the progress that pupils make from the end of key stage 1 to the end of primary school. 

The pupils’ results are compared to the actual achievements of other pupils nationally with similar key stage 1 attainment. This data measures the average progress score of all children in England with the score for particular ethnic groups.

A progress score of 0 (the national average) means pupils are making the expected amount of progress. A positive score (0.1 and above) means they are making more progress than expected, and a negative score (-0.1 and below) less progress than expected.
summary:
* in 2015/16, there were 586,157 pupils in key stage 2 at state-funded mainstream schools in England, of which ethnicity was known for 581,278 pupils (99%)

* 76% were White, 11% were Asian, 6% were Black, 5% were Mixed, 2% were any Other ethnic group and 0.4% were Chinese

The data for expected standards in maths shows that:

* looking at the national average for all pupils, 75% reached the expected standard for maths in 2015/16 

* Chinese children were most likely to meet the expected standard, with 92% of pupils doing so

* Gypsy/Roma children were least likely to meet the expected standard, with 26% of pupils doing so

* boys and girls in England were equally likely to meet the expected standard for maths, with 70% of both groups doing so

The data for higher standards in maths shows that:

* looking at the national average for all children, 17% of pupils reached the higher standard for maths in 2015/16

* Chinese children did best, with 50% of pupils meeting the higher standard

* Gypsy/Roma children were least likely to meet the higher standard, with 1% of pupils doing so

* 18% of all boys in England and 15% of all girls met the higher standard

The data for national average scaled scores for maths shows that:

* the average scaled score for maths for all pupils in England was 103

* Chinese children scored 109, the highest average score of any ethnic group

* Gypsy/Roma children scored 96, the lowest average score of any ethnic group

The data for progress scores for maths shows that:

* the average progress score for all pupils in England was 0 (a score of 0 means pupils are making the expected amount of progress)

* Chinese pupils made the most progress in maths, scoring an average of 4.5, while children from a Traveller of Irish heritage background made the least progress, scoring -1.4
need_to_know:
In the published ‘statistical first release’ (SFR) for maths standards (key stage 2), the Department of Education (DfE) has ‘suppressed’ very small numbers (for example, values of 1 or 2, a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved, or 0, 1 or 2 pupils who did not achieve a particular level).

This is because, where the size of the ethnic group population is small enough that an individual’s identity could come to light, information is excluded, or 'suppressed', to preserve confidentiality. This is consistent with [DfE’s statistical policy statement on confidentiality](https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/190768/Confidentiality_Policy_v4.pdf)
ethnicity_definition_summary:
This data uses categories from the Department of Education’s school census, which is broadly based on the 2001 national census, with two exceptions:

* Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma children have been separated into two categories

* Sri Lankan has been added to the Asian/Asian British group

These changes were made after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups.

The categories are as follows:

White:

* White British

* White Irish

* Traveller of Irish Heritage

* Gypsy/Roma

* Other White

Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups:

* White and Black Caribbean

* White and Black African

* White and Asian

* Other Mixed background

Asian/Asian British:

* Indian

* Pakistani

* Bangladeshi

* Sri Lankan

* Other Asian Background

Black/African/Caribbean/Black British:

* Black African

* Black Caribbean

* Other Black background

Other ethnic group:

* Chinese

* Other Background

Information about maths standards is provided for both detailed and broad ethnic groups categories with the exception of local authority data. Here, it is only provided for the 5 broad ethnic groups to preserve confidentiality and ensure individuals cannot be identified.

In these 5 broad ethnic groups, the school census replaces ‘Other ethnic group’ with ‘Chinese’, again after consultations with local authorities and lobby groups.

The 5 broad categories are as follows:

* White

* Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups

* Asian/Asian British

* Black/African/Caribbean/Black British

* Chinese
source_text: Key stage 2 Attainment and Progress Data
data_source_purpose: The primary purpose is to measure schools and pupils progress and performance from Key stage 1 to Key stage 2 to monitor and improve standards and inform parental choice when applying to local schools
methodology:
The key stage 2 datasets are compiled using information matched together from three data sources:

* prior attainment records (key stage 1 results)

* school census records

* qualification entries and results collected from awarding bodies

Key stage assessment data received from the Standard Testing Agency (STA) is combined with information on pupil's characteristics from the school census and prior attainment by the department's contractor.

Records are matched, using fields such as surname, forename, date of birth, UPN (unique pupil number), gender and postcode. This successfully matches around 60% to 70% of pupils.

Additional, more complex, routines are then applied to match as many of the remaining pupils as possible, up to around 98%. The coverage of the local authority (LA) and regional statistics is state-funded schools only in England.

Confidence intervals for progress results are calculated for a school based on a specific cohort of pupils. A school may have been just as effective, but have performed differently with a different set of pupils.

Similarly, some pupils may be more likely to achieve high or low results, independently of which school they attend. To account for this natural uncertainty, 95% confidence intervals around progress scores are provided as a proxy for the range of scores within which each school’s underlying performance can be confidently said to lie.

School scores should be interpreted alongside their associated confidence intervals. If the lower bound of the school’s confidence interval is greater than zero, it can be interpreted as meaning that the school has achieved greater than average progress compared to pupils with similar starting points nationally.

Similarly, if the upper bound is below zero, then the school has made less than average progress. Where a confidence interval overlaps zero, this means that the school’s progress score is not significantly different from the national average.

The system of national curriculum levels is no longer used by the government to report on end of key stage assessment.

For this reason, the previous 'expected progress' measure, based on pupils making at least two levels of progress between key stage 1 and key stage 2, will not appear in the performance tables or Reporting and Analysis for Improvement through school Self-Evaluation (RAISEonline) in 2016.

This measure has been replaced by 'value added' progress measures in reading, writing and mathematics.

There is no 'target' for the amount of progress an individual pupil is expected to make, and any amount of progress a pupil makes contributes towards the school's progress scores.

Because of the changes to the curriculum, figures for 2016 are not comparable to those for earlier years.
disclosure_control:
The Code of Practice for Official Statistics requires us to take reasonable steps to ensure that our published or disseminated statistics protect confidentiality.

In the statistical first release (SFR), an 'x' indicates that a figure has been suppressed due to small numbers. Values of 1 or 2 or a percentage based on 1 or 2 pupils who achieved, or did not achieve, a particular standard are suppressed. Some additional figures may be suppressed to prevent the possibility of a suppressed figure being revealed. This suppression is consistent with the departmental statistical policy on confidentiality.

Figures for the Isles of Scilly and City of London are suppressed in the key stage 2 provisional SFR as these LAs have a single school and we do not publish school level in the performance tables at the time of the provisional SFR. These figures become unsuppressed in the revised SFR as school level figures are already published in the performance tables. Regional eligible pupil figures are rounded to the nearest 10 so that it is not possible to derive figures for these LAs by summing the figures for the other LAs in the region.
In the school level data, any figures relating to a cohort of 5 pupils or fewer will be suppressed. This applies to sub-groups of pupils as well as the whole cohort, for example, if there were five boys and three girls in a school, we would not publish attainment for boys or girls separately but would publish attainment for all pupils as this is based on 8 pupils.
estimation: Progress scores are given to 1 decimal place

dimensions.title: Maths attainments for children aged 7 to 11 by ethnicity
dimensions.summary:
The data for expected standards in maths shows that:

* looking at the national average for all children, 70% of pupils reached the expected standard for maths in 2015/16

* the percentage of children meeting the expected standard was below the national average in the following ethnic groups: White British, Mixed White and Black African, Pakistani, Mixed White and Black Caribbean, Black Caribbean, Traveller of Irish Heritage, Gypsy/Roma and Other Black 

* 92% of Chinese pupils met the expected standard in maths, while Gypsy/Roma children did least well, with 26% meeting the expected standard in maths

The data for higher standards in maths shows that:

* looking at the national average for all children,  17% of pupils met the higher standard for maths in 2015/16

* the percentage of children meeting the higher standard was below the national average in the following ethnic groups: Pakistani, Black African, White British, Mixed White and Black African, Other Black, Mixed White and Black Caribbean, Black Caribbean, Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma 

* 50% of Chinese pupils met the higher standard in maths, while Gypsy/Roma children did least well, with 1% meeting the higher standard

The data for national average scaled scores for maths shows that:

* Chinese pupils exceeded the national average of 103, with a score of 109

* pupils from the Other Black, Mixed White and Black Caribbean, Black Caribbean, Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma groups fell below the national average for scaled scores 

* Gypsy/Roma pupils scored lowest, with an average of 96

The data for progress scores for maths shows that:

* Chinese children made the most progress, scoring 4.5, and children from a Traveller of Irish Heritage background made the least progress, scoring -1.4

dimensions.title: Maths attainments for children aged 7 to 11 by ethnicity and area
dimensions.summary:
This data for expected standards for maths shows that:

* overall, the best performing local authority was the City of London, where 100% of pupils met the expected standard – however, because there is only one school of 28 pupils in the  City of London, this result should be treated with caution

* the worst performing local authority overall was the Isles of Scilly, where 55% of pupils met the expected standard – however, because there is only one school of 20 pupils on the Isles of Scilly, this result should be treated with caution

* the top performing local authorities for White pupils were all in London: the City of London, Kensington and Chelsea and Lambeth

* the local authorities with the lowest proportion of White pupils reaching the expected standard were the Isles of Scilly in the South West and Peterborough, Bedford and Norfolk in the East of England

* Asian pupils were most likely to meet the expected standard in the City of London, Bromley and Sutton in London

* Asian pupils were least likely to meet the expected standard on the Isle of Wight in the South West

* 100% of Chinese pupils met the expected standard in maths in 47 local authorities

* Chinese pupils were least likely to meet the expected standard in Worcestershire in the West Midlands and West Sussex and East Sussex in the South East 

* Black pupils were most likely to meet the expected standard in the City of London and Kensington and Chelsea in London, Gateshead in the North East and Blackburn with Darwen in the North West

* Black pupils were least likely to meet the expected standard in Bath and North East in the South West, North Lincolnshire in Yorkshire and The Humber and Cambridgeshire in the East of England

* for Mixed race pupils, the best performing local authorities were Redcar and Cleveland in the North East, Warrington, Cumbria and St. Helens in the North West and North Yorkshire in Yorkshire and The Humber

* Mixed race pupils were least likely to meet the expected standard in Sunderland in the North East, Peterborough in the East of England and Kirklees in Yorkshire and The Humber

dimensions.title: Maths attainments for children aged 7 to 11 by ethnicity and gender
dimensions.summary:
The data for expected standards in maths shows that:

* boys and girls in England were equally likely to meet the expected standard for maths, with 70% of each group doing so

* White British girls, Gypsy/Roma girls, Pakistani girls and girls from the Other White background were less likely to meet the expected standards than boys; in all other ethnic groups, girls did as well as or better than boys

* Chinese boys and girls did best, with 92% of boys and 92% of girls meeting the expected standard

* Gypsy/Roma boys and girls were least likely to meet the expected standard, with 26% of boys and 25% of girls doing so

The data for higher standards in maths shows that:

* overall, 18% of boys and 15% of girls met the higher standard

* boys did better than girls in all ethnic groups

* Chinese boys did best, with 53% meeting the higher standard

The data for national average scaled scores for maths shows that:

* the national average for both boys and girls was a score of 103

* both boys and girls from the following ethnic groups achieved scores below the national average: White and Black Caribbean, Black Caribbean, Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma

* Pakistani girls and girls from the Other Black background also fell below the national average  

* Chinese boys and girls did best, with average scaled scores of 110 and 109 respectively

* both boys and girls from the following ethnic groups achieved scores above the national average: Indian, Other Asian, Mixed White and Asian, Irish, Bangladeshi and the Other ethnic group

* boys from the Other White and Other Mixed groups also achieved scores above the national average

* the ethnic groups with the lowest scores were boys and girls from a Traveller of Irish Heritage background (96 and 97, respectively) and Gypsy/Roma boys and girls (96 for both)

The data for progress scores for maths shows that:

* the national average progress score in maths is 0 (a score of 0 means pupils are making the expected amount of progress)

* overall, boys made more progress than girls in maths – boys scored 0.6, and girls scored -0.6

* boys and girls from the following ethnic groups fell below the national average progress score of 0: White British, White and Black African, Black Caribbean, Mixed White and Black Caribbean, Traveller of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma

* girls from the Other Mixed group also fell below the national average  

* Chinese boys and girls made the most progress in maths, scoring 5.4 and 3.6, respectively

* boys from a Traveller of Irish heritage background scored -1.2

* girls from a Traveller of Irish Heritage background and Gypsy/Roma girls scored -1.6
dimensions.source: Key stage 2 Attainment and Progress Data
